# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: public-health-informatics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In public health, **contact tracing** is the process of identifying people who may have been exposed to an infected person ("contacts") and subsequent collection of further data to assess transmission.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] By tracing the contacts of infected individuals, testing them for infection, and isolating or treating the infected, this public health tool aims to reduce infections in the population.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In addition to infection control, contact tracing serves as a means to identify high-risk and medically vulnerable populations who might be exposed to infection and facilitate appropriate medical care.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In doing so, public health officials utilize contact tracing to conduct disease surveillance and prevent outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In cases of diseases of uncertain infectious potential, contact tracing is also sometimes performed to learn about disease characteristics, including infectiousness.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing is not always the most efficient method of addressing infectious disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In areas of high disease prevalence, screening or focused testing may be more cost-effective.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Alerting the general public about exposures or outbreaks of COVID-19, Measles, TB, etc.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Being a tool in multifaceted prevention strategy to effectively curb the spread of an infectious disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing programs were first implemented to track syphilis cases in the 1930s.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Initial efforts proved to be difficult given the stigmatization associated with sexually transmitted infections (STIs).
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Individuals were reluctant to report infections because they were concerned for their privacy.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Revealing partner history and details about sexual activity was challenging as it affected relationships among individuals and community members.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In addition, public health officials targeted certain populations such as sex workers, minorities, and at-risk populations further eliciting feeling of fear, shame, and guilt in society.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] With these negative implications of contact tracing, particularly in the space of sexually transmitted infections, public health officials found it difficult to elicit information from exposed individuals.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] During the HIV epidemic, many affected people were hesitant to report information, which hindered the efforts to understand HIV and curb the spread.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] To combat some of the negative stigma associated with contact tracing and STIs, health departments sometimes referred to contact tracing as partner notification in the 1980s.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Partner notification, also called partner care, is a subset of contact tracing aimed specifically at informing sexual partners of an infected person and addressing their health needs.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This definition evolved from identifying infected individuals to including a comprehensive program that encompasses counseling and medical care to treat the infection.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The official title, contract tracers, was first implemented in the United Kingdom during the smallpox outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Dedicated individuals served on a surveillance-based team to curb the spread of disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This process served as a blueprint for other public health agencies to have a formalized program.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The United States soon followed and enacted a contact tracing program for the prevention of infectious diseases which included TB, HIV, SARS, and now SARS-CoV-2.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] **Contact interview:** The index case is interviewed to learn about their movements, whom they have been in close contact with or who their sexual partners have been.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Depending on the disease and the context of the infection, family members, health care providers, and anyone else who may have knowledge of the case's contacts may also be interviewed.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Interviews typically follow a template which include demographics, symptomology, pre-existing conditions, and timing of exposures to ensure consistency across all contact tracing efforts.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Interpreters and source materials in different languages are utilized to accommodate persons with different cultural backgrounds.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] **Recommendations for close contacts:** Once contacts are identified, public health workers contact them to offer counseling, screening, prophylaxis, and/or treatment.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contacts are provided education on concepts of quarantine, isolation, signs and symptoms of disease, and timely testing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] If applicable, contacts should wear appropriate personal protective equipment to reduce to transmission of disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] **Assessing feasibility of self-quarantine and support:** Contacts may be isolated (e.g. required to remain at home) or excluded (e.g. prohibited from attending a particular location, like a school) if deemed necessary for disease control.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Challenges for this process include access to resources during quarantine such as food, water, and safe living environment.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] People with special roles lack the convenience practicing quarantine given their daily responsibilities.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Examples include, single parents, caregivers, and individuals with toddlers.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Social services and ancillary support from the government become crucial to maintaining measures of quarantine and isolation.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contacts should be made aware whether or not the quarantine or isolation is voluntary or mandatory.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Depending on the nature of the disease of interest, governments can issue legal orders to maintain integrity of contact tracing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] **Medical monitoring:** Although contact tracing can be enhanced by letting patients provide information, medication, and referrals to their contacts, evidence demonstrates that direct public health involvement in notification is most effective.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Ideally, contacts are checked upon daily for signs and symptoms of disease by contact racers.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] An alternative would be having the contacts report daily to their assigned official.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This is usually done through digital platforms such as email and text.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] If a contact is symptomatic, a case investigator is assignment to direct the individual to the appropriate testing and treatment.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This stage of contact tracing is highly dependent on resource availability.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] **Contact close out:** This stage is dependent on the duration of quarantine for people with and without symptoms.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The ideal number of days for quarantine and isolation are determined by the health agencies.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Once the contact adequately completes the quarantine/isolation for the defined number of days, they can be closed out.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Next steps such as returning to work and participating in social activities are discussed.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The types of contacts that are relevant for public health management vary because of differing modes of transmission.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] For sexually transmitted infections, sexual contacts of the index case are relevant, as well as any babies born to the index case.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This information is crucial for investigating congenital syphilis cases for example.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] For blood-borne infections, blood transfusion recipients, contacts who shared a needle, and anyone else who could have been exposed to the blood of the index case are relevant.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This information becomes relevant for health systems to keep track of high risk populations and medical errors, unavoidable and preventable.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] For pulmonary tuberculosis, people living in the same household or spending a significant amount of time in the same room as the index case are relevant.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Understanding the pathology and transmissibility of the disease guides the approach to contact tracing strategy.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Although contact tracing is most commonly used for control of diseases, it is also a critical tool for investigating new diseases or unusual outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] For example, as was the case with SARS, contact tracing can be used to determine if probable cases are linked to known cases of the disease, and to determine if secondary transmission is taking place in a particular community.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing has also been initiated among flight passengers during the containment phase of larger pandemics, such as the 2009 pandemic H1NI influenza.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing played a major role in investigating Ebola virus in the UK in 2014 and monkeypox in the UK in 2018.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The eradication of smallpox, for example, was achieved by exhaustive contact tracing to find all infected persons.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This was followed by isolation of infected individuals and immunization of the surrounding community and contacts at-risk of contracting smallpox.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing can help identify the etiology of a disease outbreak.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In 1984, contact tracing provided the first direct evidence that AIDS may be spread by an infectious agent during sexual contacts.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The infective agent has since been identified as HIV.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Diseases for which contact tracing is commonly performed include tuberculosis, vaccine-preventable infections like measles, sexually transmitted infections (including HIV), blood-borne infections, Ebola, bacterial infections, and novel virus infections (e.g., SARS-CoV, H1N1, and SARS-CoV-2).
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing has been a pillar of communicable disease control in public health for decades.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] With each outbreak and disease presenting with its own challenges, contact tracing is an adaptable tool used by authorities to identify, notify, and curb transmission of infections.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Backward (or reverse) tracing seeks to establish the source of an infection, by looking for contacts before infection.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] It can be used when a source of the infection is unknown and in situations of minimally monitored settings.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The goal is identify the exposures associated with the index case and secondary exposures of those contact to halt the cycle of transmission.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] During the COVID-19 pandemic, the adoption by Japan in early spring 2020 of an approach focusing on backward contact tracing was hailed as successful, and other countries which managed to keep the epidemic under control, such as South Korea and Uruguay, are said to have also used the approach.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In the United States, contact tracing had suboptimal impact on SARS-CoV-2 transmission, largely because 2 of 3 cases were either not reached for interview or named no contacts when interviewed.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Engagement in contact tracing was positively correlated with isolation and quarantine.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] However, most adults with COVID-19 isolated and self-notified contacts regardless of whether the public health workforce was able to reach them.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Identifying and reaching contacts was challenging and limited the ability to promote quarantining, and testing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Forward tracing is the process of looking for contacts after infection, so as to prevent further disease spread.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] It is the more conventional way to investigate cases and inform close contacts to either quarantine or isolate.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] For epidemics with high heterogeneity in infectiousness, adopting a hybrid strategy of forward contact tracing combined with contact tracing backwards is often used.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Backward contact tracing is beneficial for identifying clusters of spreader events, while forward tracing can be used mitigate future transmission.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The effectiveness of both approaches is limited by the resources dedicated to contact tracing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Journalist and author Laurie Garrett pointed out in late October 2020, however, that the amount of the virus in the U.S. is now so large that no health departments has the resources to contact and trace.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Additionally, officials overlooked the effect of mistrust in the government and conspiracy theories regarding the virus on thwarting contact tracing efforts in the U.S.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing requires tremendous resources and work hours to effectively contain an infection.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The COVID-19 pandemic is an unprecedented period where contact tracing and public health efforts were put to the test.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Creative strategies were used to sustain public health efforts.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Non-health personnel and volunteers were used to meet the shortage of contact tracers.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Existing infrastructure such as call centers and national helpline services were used for operations.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Individuals who were the most sick and medically vulnerable were prioritized as contacts over healthier people.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The advent of technology and digital tracing tools were implemented at a global scale without much vetting and testing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Various countries had different adaptations and outcomes with contact tracing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] China used pre-existing WeChat and Alipay platforms to track person health status and travel patterns.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Singapore, South Korea, and Vietnam had success limiting the initial spread of the virus.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] With contact tracing, once a person was identified to be exposed, they were immediately isolated.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In some instances the government provided housing for isolation to limit movements.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In Turkey, the government launched a public forum that highlighted risk zones in various regions of the country.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Residents can self-report their health status and track areas with reported high rates of transmission.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In the United States, contact tracing efforts varied by the respective health department in a particular state.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Overall, effectiveness of contact tracing data in the country was determined by the caseload assigned to contact tracers.Natural experiments confirmed the effectiveness of contact tracing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] When on-demand testing was promoted, increases in negative tests were followed by increases in hospitalizations.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Subsequent studies of cases and deaths found the same results.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] If increased testing were in response to surges, more testing should follow increases in cases, not precede them.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] An average of 208 extra miles were accumulated in the week following each negative test in U.S. counties.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] These results suggest that people who tested negative underestimated the risk of exposure when they traveled or visited.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] As self-administered, home-based tests became increasingly used as the primary method to detect SARS-CoV-2, fewer cases were reached for case investigation and contact tracing by public health departments.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] As a result, fewer cases followed contemporary isolation recommendations.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The age of digital contact tracing started gaining traction during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] With widespread transmission and shortage of contact tracers, technology serves as a resource to bridge gaps.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In addition, digital applications automate the process and replace the manual steps contact tracers take to track and notify exposed individuals.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] There are few benefits of using digital contract tracing apps over the traditional manual methods.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Manual methods require a skilled workforce who put in significant hours to diligently follow the steps in contact tracing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This requires a heavy investment from the government, which at times is not feasible.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Manual contact tracing is not suited to detect exposures unknown to the contact, as the process is limited to the interview and known knowledge.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Areas such as restaurants and malls make it almost impossible for the contact to know whether they have been exposed.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] At a theoretical scale, digital applications propose mechanism to effectively prevent and stop epidemics.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] During the COVID-19 pandemic, manual contact tracers used technology to augment their tracing efforts.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Case managers in particular were a group of professionals that benefited from this resource.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Case management software is often used by contact tracers to maintain records of cases and contact tracing activities.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This is typically a cloud database that may have specialized features such as the ability to use SMS or email directly within the software to notify people believed to have been in close contact with someone carrying an infectious disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Utilizing a database, provides benefit to track persons of interest and offers a platforms to look at data points such as race, zip code, and symptoms.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Vendors offering contact tracing case management software include Salesforce, Microsoft and Watkyn.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] South Korea became a pioneer in utilizing digital contact tracing tools.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Learning lessons from the MERS outbreak in 2015, the government executed a robust contact tracing program.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Global positioning system (GPS) technology was used to track movement of individuals and appropriately notify persons who have been exposed.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The South Korean government launched the Corona 100m application to implement their digital contact tracing measures.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The application allowed the public health agencies to track super spreader events, inform the public, and guide them to treatment if applicable.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] At the end of April 2020, South Korea reported over 10,000 infections and 204 deaths, numbers which were vastly superior to contemporaries in the European Union.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Singapore was among the first countries to use Bluetooth technology in their contact tracing efforts.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] They launched the application—TraceTogether—which allowed smartphones to provide proximity information useful for contact tracing .
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Unlike South Korea, which utilized a central database to track cases, the Bluetooth-based apps reported information to an encrypted database that automatically deleted information after 14 days.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The western world shortly followed and started developing their own Bluetooth-based applications.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Facebook Labs patented the use of Bluetooth on smartphones for this in 2018.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] On 10 April 2020, Apple and Google, which account for most of the world's mobile operating systems, announced COVID-19 apps for iOS and Android.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Relying on Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) wireless radio signals for proximity information, the new tools would warn people that they had been in contact with who are infected by SARS-CoV-2.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] With the use of technology, certain limitations and challenges come with the territory.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Tracking technology might not accurately notify individuals who have been exposed.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Bluetooth does not differentiate between walls and structure, prompting incorrect notification of exposures.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] For instance, people separated by walls in an office building can be notified as exposed, even if they never interfaced with the contact.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Moreover, the parameters set by the developers to contact trace vary and can miss potential cases.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Such parameters include proximity or distance to trigger an exposure and the timeframe in which contacts are considered to be infectious (usually 14 days).
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Smartphone applications require people having access to smartphones and a competent infrastructure to provide internet access to the public.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Not all countries can provide these services to their residents.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Individuals must download the application, navigate the technology, and follow appropriate directions when notified.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This becomes highly difficult when the use of smartphone applications is not mandated.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Cohort studies which looked at the efficacy of digital contact tracing reported limited sensitivity in accurately catching cases due to the limitations mentioned above.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In Pennsylvania, a digital exposure notification app for COVID-19 was downloaded by 5.7% of population (635,612 people).
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Unfortunately, only 0.1% of all reported cases in Pennsylvania used the app to notify their potential contacts of exposure during the study period (390 persons), resulting in 233 notifications as compared an estimated 573,298 eligible contacts.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Challenges with contact tracing can arise related to issues of medical privacy and confidentiality.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Public health practitioners often are mandated reporters, required to act to contain a communicable disease within a broader population and also ethically obliged to warn individuals of their exposure.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Simultaneously, infected individuals have a recognized right to medical confidentiality.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Public health teams typically disclose the minimum amount of information required to achieve the objectives of contact tracing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] For example, contacts are only told that they have been exposed to a particular infection, but not informed of the person who was the source of the exposure.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] In the United States, HIPAA is a legal measure for protecting health information.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This ensures sharing of only relevant information in the contact tracing process.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] However, given the unprecedented spread and mortality of SARS-CoV2, advocacy groups argue the protections offered by HIPAA are spread thin.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Some activists and health care providers have expressed concerns that contact tracing may discourage persons from seeking medical treatment for fear of loss of confidentiality and subsequent stigma, discrimination, or abuse.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] This has been of particular concern regarding contact tracing for HIV.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Public health officials have recognized that the goals of contact tracing must be balanced with the maintenance of trust with vulnerable populations and sensitivity to individual situations.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Privacy is still a concern even if individual information is not disclosed by public health practitioners.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The data collected in databases by governments and tech companies could be utilized for unrelated purposes.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Big tech companies have access to data which provides insight on where people visit, what types of interests they pursue, and who interacts with each other.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Therefore, questions regarding the extent of data collected, how long the information is stored, who it is shared with, and for what purpose it is being utilized come with serious ethical considerations.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Contact tracing efforts miss vulnerable and under resourced populations.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Manual tracing efforts face difficulty tracking hard to reach individuals given social complexities.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Digital tools require a smart phone and a reliable internet connection, two factors that might exclude certain individuals from benefiting from the technology.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Data is still pre-mature as to the efficacy of digital tools.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Some stakeholders argue whether it is appropriate to shift contact tracing into a complete digital capacity.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Safeguards become topics of contention when designing digital contact tracing tools.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Restrictions on which tracking software such as GPS, Wi-Fi, and Bluetooth are used and when those services are turned on are debated among stakeholders.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Who has access to the date is an important ethical issue as well.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Centralized vs. de-centralized databases have been implemented across the world during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] The culture within a nation and those who run the government have a huge role in deciding in what players have access to data.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Therefore, governing bodies have to consider ethical principles related to transparency and accountability to the public.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Moreover, whether participating in contact tracing efforts should be voluntary or mandatory is another ethical dilemma that adds to the complexity of implementation.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] As noted above, there are numerous ethical and legal factors that go into implementation of contact tracing.
[src:public-health-informatics/contact-tracing] Executing a robust contact tracing program requires resources, skilled professionals, and an ethical framework that complies with the fabric of a particular nation.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] The **Global Public Health Intelligence Network** (GPHIN) is an electronic public health early warning system developed by Canada's Public Health Agency, and is part of the World Health Organization's (WHO) Global Outbreak Alert and Response Network (GOARN).
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] This system monitors internet media, such as news wires and websites, in nine languages in order to help detect and report potential disease or other health threats around the world.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] The system has been credited with detecting early signs of the 2009 swine flu pandemic in Mexico, Zika in West Africa, H5N1 in Iran, MERS and Ebola.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] The system came to greater public awareness after it was revealed that Canada's Federal Government effectively shut it down in May 2019, ultimately preventing the system from providing an early warning of COVID-19.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] In August 2020, the system began issuing alerts again.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] John, then a government epidemiologist, created GPHIN in 1994 as a way to improve Canada's intelligence surrounding outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] After the 2003 SARS outbreak, the system became central to Canada's pandemic preparedness.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] The system, which eventually fell under the Centre for Emergency Preparedness and Response in the PHAC, detected early signs of the 2009 swine flu pandemic in Mexico, Zika in West Africa, H5N1 in Iran, MERS and Ebola.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] A July 2020 investigation by *The Globe and Mail* revealed that Canada's Federal Government effectively shutdown GPHIN in May 2019, ultimately preventing the system from providing an early warning of COVID-19.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] After the government directed for a more domestic focus, the Public Health Agency of Canada (PHAC) assigned employees to different tasks in the department.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] The shutdown was gradual: in 2009, there were 877 alerts; 198 in 2013; and only 21 in 2018.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] In August 2020, more than 400 days after going silent, the system began issuing alerts again.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] In early 2020 before COVID-19 was declared a pandemic, scientists at PHAC "were told to focus on official information coming out of China, rather than unofficial intelligence.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] Following *The Globe and Mail's* report, Canada's Auditor-General began an investigation into why the program was curtailed.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] Released in March 2021, the Auditor-General's report described PHAC as ill-prepared for the pandemic.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] The report focused primarily on the silencing of GPHIN and the inaccurate risk assessments that replaced it.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] In September 2020, Canada's Health Minister Patty Hajdu ordered an independent federal review to look into both the shutdown of the system along with allegations that some scientist's voices were marginalized.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] Former national security adviser Margaret Bloodworth; former deputy chief public health officer Paul Gully; and Mylaine Breton, Canada Research Chair in Clinical Governance on Primary Health Care led Hajdu's review.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] Canada's Chief Public Health Officer Theresa Tam announced her support of the review, while Prime Minister Justin Trudeau issued blame to funding cuts made prior to 2015 by the previous Conservative government under Stephen Harper.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] PHAC's Centre for Emergency Preparedness and Response (CEPR) manages GPHIN.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] In October 2020, Jim Harris was director-general CEPR.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] In September 2020 Brigitte Diogo replaced Sally Thornton as vice-president of the Health Security Infrastructure Branch, the bureaucratic division overseeing GPHIN among other operations.
[src:public-health-informatics/global-public-health-intelligence-network] A week later, President Tina Namiesniowski announced her resignation, with Trudeau nominating Iain Stewart as her successor.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] A **notifiable disease** is any disease that is required by law to be reported to government authorities.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The collation of information allows the authorities to monitor the disease, and provides early warning of possible outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] In the case of livestock diseases, there may also be the legal requirement to kill the infected livestock upon notification.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Many governments have enacted regulations for reporting of both human and animal (generally livestock) diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The World Health Organization's *International Health Regulations 1969* require disease reporting to the organization in order to help with its global surveillance and advisory role.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The current (1969) regulations are rather limited with a focus on reporting of three main diseases: cholera, yellow fever and plague.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Smallpox was a contagious disease during the 18th-20th century.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] It was endemic until mass vaccination, after which WHO certified Smallpox to be eradicated.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] This marked the first (and thus far only) human disease to be successfully eradicated.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The revised *International Health Regulations 2005* broadens this scope and is no longer limited to the notification of specific diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Whilst it does identify a number of specific diseases, it also defines a limited set of criteria to assist in deciding whether an event is notifiable to WHO.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] WHO states that "Notification is now based on the identification within a State Party’s territory of an "event that may constitute a public health emergency of international concern".
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] This non-disease specific definition of notifiable events expands the scope of the IHR (2005) to include any novel or evolving risk to international public health, taking into account the context in which the event occurs.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Such notifiable events can extend beyond communicable diseases and arise from any origin or source.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The OIE (World Organisation for Animal Health) monitors specific animal diseases on a global scale.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The National Notifiable Diseases Surveillance System (NNDSS) was established in 1990.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Notifications are made to the States or Territory health authority and computerised, de-identified records are then supplied to the Department of Health and Ageing for collation, analysis and publication.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The Australian national notifiable diseases list and case definitions are available online.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Within Australia the Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry regulates the notification of infectious animal diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Notification is regulated under Brazilian Ministry of Health Ordinance number 1.271 of June 6, 2014.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Diseases of concern to public health officials have been tracked in Canada since 1924.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] A subcommittee of the National Advisory Committee on Epidemiology was set up in 1987.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] At the time, 34 diseases were surveyed on the list of **communicable diseases** while another 13 were recommended for addition to the list.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] As of 1 January 2000, a total of 43 diseases were given the status of notifiable.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] In 2006, the *Final report and recommendations from the National Notifiable Diseases Working Group* found that certain diseases should be added and certain diseases should not.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The **Canadian Notifiable Disease Surveillance System** is a searchable database tool provided by the Public Health Agency of Canada.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The first policies of mandatory notifiable disease originated a long time ago in France, while exact times are unclear we know that at the end of the 18th century Plague was a highly enforced notifiable disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Anonymous records are then used by the government health-insurance system.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Ill people must cure them and in many case are put in quarantine.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Only infectious diseases are notifiable to the authorities.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The complete list can be found in the *Article L.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] 223-22 du code rural*, it is updated with every new entry on World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) lists A and B and with European Union mandatory lists.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Notification is regulated under the *Health Act 1956*, except for tuberculosis which is regulated under the *Tuberculosis Act 1948*.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Requirement for the notification of infectious diseases originated near the end of the 19th century.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The list started with a few select diseases and has since grown to 31.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] Currently disease notification for humans in the UK is regulated under the *Public Health (Control of Disease) Act 1984* and *Public Health (Infectious Diseases) Regulations 1988*.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The governing body is Public Health England Public Health England List of Notifiable Diseases can be found here Notifiable diseases and causative organisms: how to report.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] In the UK notification of diseases in animals is regulated by the Animal Health Act 1981, as well as the *Specified Diseases (Notification and Slaughter) Order 1992 (as amended)* and *Specified Diseases (Notification) Order 1996 (as amended)*.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The act states that a police constable should be notified, however in practice a Defra divisional veterinary manager is notified and Defra will investigate.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] In the past, notifiable diseases in the United States varied according to the laws of individual states.
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the Council of State and Territorial Epidemiologists (CSTE) also produced a list of nationally notifiable diseases that health officials should report to the CDC's National Notifiable Diseases Surveillance System (NNDSS).
[src:public-health-informatics/notifiable-disease] A uniform criterion for reporting diseases to the NNDSS was introduced in 1990.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The structure of public health informatics data collection and management in the United States is divided among both the federal and state levels.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) is the department at the federal level, and locally, it belongs to the state departments of health.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] These programs have standardized the reporting of digital health data by hospitals and clinics.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The government departments can then gather this data, analyze it, and use it for a variety of purposes.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Such purposes typically fall under the three major domains of public health informatics: understanding more about complex processes that occur, storing a record of public health data, and analyzing and publicizing a general version of gathered data for public consumption.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Additionally, data collected from social media can also be included in these processes, refining its accuracy.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Job opportunities in this field include positions with the CDC and the American Medical Informatics Association, which provides more information about informatics for professionals in medical fields.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] In developed countries like the United States, public health informatics is practiced by individuals in public health agencies at the federal and state levels and in the larger local health jurisdictions.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Additionally, research and training in public health informatics takes place at a variety of academic institutions.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The bulk of the work of public health informatics in the United States, as with public health generally, takes place at the state and local level, in the state departments of health and the county or parish departments of health.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Each of these activities presents its own information processing challenge.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Since the beginning of the World Wide Web, public health agencies with sufficient information technology resources have been transitioning to web-based collection of public health data, and, more recently, to automated messaging of the same information.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] In the years roughly 2000 to 2005 the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, under its National Electronic Disease Surveillance System (NEDSS), built and provided free to states a comprehensive web and message-based reporting system called the NEDSS Base System (NBS).
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Due to the funding being limited and it not being wise to have fiefdom-based systems, only a few states and larger counties have built their own versions of electronic disease surveillance systems, such as Pennsylvania's PA-NEDSS.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] These do not provide timely full intestate notification services causing an increase in disease rates versus the NEDSS federal product.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] To promote interoperability, the CDC has encouraged the adoption in public health data exchange of several standard vocabularies and messaging formats from the health care world.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The most prominent of these are: the Health Level 7 (HL7) standards for health care messaging; the LOINC system for encoding laboratory test and result information; and the Systematized Nomenclature of Medicine (SNOMED) vocabulary of health care concepts.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] At each stage the entity must be capable of receiving the data, storing it, aggregating it appropriately, and transmitting it to the next level.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] A typical example would be infectious disease data, which hospitals, labs, and doctors are legally required to report to local health agencies; local health agencies must report to their state public health department; and which the states must report in aggregate form to the CDC.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Among other uses, the CDC publishes the Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR) based on these data acquired systematically from across the United States.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Public health informatics can be thought of or divided into three categories.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The first category is to discover and study models of complex systems, such as disease transmission.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] This can be done through different types of data collections, such as hospital surveys, or electronic surveys submitted to the organization (such as the CDC).
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Transmission rates or disease incidence rates/surveillance can be obtained through government organizations, such as the CDC, or global organizations, such as WHO.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Not only disease transmission/rates can be looked at.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Public health informatics can also delve into people with/without health insurance and the rates at which they go to the doctor.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Before the advent of the internet, public health data in the United States, like other healthcare and business data, were collected on paper forms and stored centrally at the relevant public health agency.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] If the data were to be computerized they required a distinct data entry process, were stored in the various file formats of the day and analyzed by mainframe computers using standard batch processing.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The second category is to find ways to improve the efficiency of different public health systems.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] This is done through various collections methods, storage of data and how the data is used to improve current health problems.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] In order to keep everything standardized, vocabulary and word usage needs to be consistent throughout all systems.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Finding new ways to link together and share new data with current systems is important to keep everything up to date.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Storage of public health data shares the same data management issues as other industries.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Like other industries, the details of how these issues play out are affected by the nature of the data being managed.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Due to the complexity and variability of public health data, like health care data generally, the issue of data modeling presents a particular challenge.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] While a generation ago flat data sets for statistical analysis were the norm, today's requirements of interoperability and integrated sets of data across the public health enterprise require more sophistication.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The relational database is increasingly the norm in public health informatics.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Due to the variability of the incoming data to public health jurisdictions, data quality assurance is also a major issue.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Finally, the last category can be thought as maintaining and enriching current systems and models to adapt to overflow of data and storing/sorting of this new data.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] This can be as simple as connecting directly to an electronic data collection source, such as health records from the hospital, or can go public information (CDC) about disease rates/transmission.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Finding new algorithms that will sort through large quantities of data quickly and effectively is necessary as well.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Such analyses usually require methods that appropriately secure the privacy of the health data.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] One approach is to separate the individually identifiable variables of the data from the rest.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Another broader approach is to use social media to analyze health trends.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Since the late 2000s, data from social media websites such as Twitter and Facebook, as well as search engines such as Google and Bing, have been used extensively in detecting trends in public health.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] There are a few organizations out there that provide useful information for those professionals that want to be more involved in public health informatics.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Such as the American Medical Informatics Association (AMIA).
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] AMIA is for professions that are involved in health care, informatics research, biomedical research, including physicians, scientists, researchers, and students.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The main goals of AMIA are to move from 'bench to bedside', help improve the impact of health innovations and advance the public health informatics field.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] They hold annual conferences, online classes and webinars, which are free to their members.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] There is also a career center specific for the biomedical and health informatics community.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] Many jobs or fellowships in public health informatics are offered.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-informatics] The CDC (Center for Disease Control) has various fellowship programs, while multiple colleges/companies offer degree programs or training in this field.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Public health surveillance systems can be passive or active.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] A passive surveillance system consists of the regular, ongoing reporting of diseases and conditions by all health facilities in a given territory.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] An active surveillance system is one where health facilities are visited and health care providers and medical records are reviewed in order to identify a specific disease or condition.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Passive surveillance systems are less time-consuming and less expensive to run but risk under-reporting of some diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Active surveillance systems are most appropriate for epidemics or where a disease has been targeted for elimination.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Techniques of public health surveillance have been used in particular to study infectious diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Many regions and countries have their own cancer registry, which monitors the incidence of cancers to determine the prevalence and possible causes of these illnesses.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Other illnesses such as one-time events like stroke and chronic conditions such as diabetes, as well as social problems such as domestic violence, are increasingly being integrated into epidemiologic databases called disease registries.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] A cost-benefit analysis is conducted on these registries to determine governmental funding for research and prevention.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Systems that can automate the process of identifying adverse drug events, are currently being used, and are being compared to traditional written reports of such events.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] These systems intersect with the field of medical informatics, and are rapidly becoming adopted by hospitals and endorsed by institutions that oversee healthcare providers (such as JCAHO in the United States).
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Issues in regard to healthcare improvement are evolving around the surveillance of medication errors within institutions.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Syndromic surveillance is the analysis of medical data to detect or anticipate disease outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] According to a CDC definition, "the term 'syndromic surveillance' applies to surveillance using health-related data that precede diagnosis and signal a sufficient probability of a case or an outbreak to warrant further public health response.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The first indications of disease outbreak or bioterrorist attack may not be the definitive diagnosis of a physician or a lab.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Syndromic surveillance systems monitor data from school absenteeism logs, emergency call systems, hospitals' over-the-counter drug sale records, Internet searches, and other data sources to detect unusual patterns.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] When a spike in activity is seen in any of the monitored systems disease epidemiologists and public health professionals are alerted that there may be an issue.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] An early awareness and response to a bioterrorist attack could save many lives and potentially stop or slow the spread of the outbreak.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] A syndromic surveillance system based on search queries was first proposed by Gunther Eysenbach, who began work on such a system in 2004.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Inspired by these early, encouraging experiences, Google launched Google Flu Trends in 2008.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] More flu-related searches are taken to indicate higher flu activity.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The results, which were published in Nature, closely matched CDC data, and led it by 1–2 weeks.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] However, it has been shown that the original approach behind Google Flu Trends had various modelling deficiencies leading to significant errors in its estimates.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] More recently, a series of more advanced linear and nonlinear approaches to influenza modeling from Google search queries have been proposed.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Extending Google's work researchers from the Intelligent Systems Laboratory (University of Bristol, UK) created Flu Detector; an online tool which based on Information Retrieval and Statistical Analysis methods uses the content of Twitter to nowcast flu rates in the UK.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Digital surveillance of public health largely relies on a number of methods.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The most important ones being the use of search-based trends on sites like Google and Wikipedia, social media posts on platforms like Facebook and Twitter, and participatory surveillance websites such as Flu Near You and Influenzanet.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] However the range of potential data sources suitable for disease surveillance has increased as different areas have become digitized; today school attendance records, hospital emergency admissions data and even sales data, can be used for syndromic surveillance purposes.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Search trends provide indirect data on public health, while the latter two methods provide direct data.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Search aggregates have been most frequently used to track and model influenza.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] A popular example is Google Flu Trends, which was first released in 2008.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Wikipedia has also been used, though it is potentially prone to "noise", as it is a popular source of health information whether a user is ill or not.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] During the COVID-19 pandemic a new methodology has been developed to model COVID-19 prevalence based on web search activity.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] This methodology has also been used by Public Health England in the United Kingdom as one of their syndromic surveillance endpoints.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Examples of social media public health surveillance include HealthTweets, which gathers data from Twitter.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Twitter data is considered highly useful for public health research, as its data policies allow public access to 1% samples of raw tweets.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Tweets can also be geolocated, which can be used to model the spread of contagious disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] It is the most used social media platform for public health surveillance.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Facebook used aggregated, anonymized data collected from its platforms to provide human movement information to disease models.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] It also offered users a chance to participate in a disease symptom survey through Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Flu Near You and Influenzanet are two examples of crowd-sourced digital surveillance systems.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Both sites recruit users to participate in surveys about influenza symptoms.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Influenzanet was established in 2009, and operates in ten countries in Europe.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Its predecessor was Grote Griepmeting, which was a Dutch/Belgian platform launched in 2003 and 2004.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Another example of a surveillance sites is Dengue na Web, used to survey for dengue fever in Bahia, Brazil.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Some conditions, especially chronic diseases such as diabetes mellitus, are supposed to be routinely managed with frequent laboratory measurements.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Since many laboratory results, at least in Europe and the US, are automatically processed by computerized laboratory information systems, the results are relatively easy to inexpensively collate in special purpose databases or disease registries.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Unlike most syndromic surveillance systems, in which each record is assumed to be independent of the others, laboratory data in chronic conditions can be theoretically linked together at the individual patient level.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] If patient identifiers can be matched, a chronological record of each patient's laboratory results can be analyzed as well as aggregated to the population level.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Laboratory registries allow for the analysis of the incidence and prevalence of the target condition as well as trends in the level of control.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] For instance, an NIH-funded program called the Vermedx Diabetes Information System maintained a registry of laboratory values of diabetic adults in Vermont and northern New York State in the US with several years of laboratory results on thousands of patients.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The data included measures of blood sugar control (glycated hemoglobin A1c), cholesterol, and kidney function (serum creatinine and urine protein), and were used to monitor the quality of care at the patient, practice, and population levels.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Since the data contained each patient's name and address, the system was also used to communicate directly with patients when the laboratory data indicated the need for attention.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Out of control test results generated a letter to the patient suggesting they take action with their medical provider.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Tests that were overdue generated reminders to have testing performed.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The system also generated reminders and alerts with guideline-based advice for the practice as well as a periodic roster of each provider's patients and a report card summarizing the health status of the population.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Clinical and economic evaluations of the system, including a large randomized clinical trial, demonstrated improvements in adherence to practice guidelines and reductions in the need for emergency department and hospital services as well as total costs per patient.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The system has been commercialized and distributed to physicians, insurers, employers and others responsible for the care of chronically ill patients.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] It is now being expanded to other conditions such as chronic kidney disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] A similar system, The New York City A1C Registry, is in used to monitor the estimated 600,000 diabetic patients in New York City, although unlike the Vermont Diabetes Information System, there are no provisions for patients to have their data excluded from the NYC database.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The NYC Department of Health and Mental Hygiene has linked additional patient services to the registry such as health information and improved access to health care services.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] As of early 2012, the registry contains over 10 million test results on 3.6 million individuals.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Although intended to improve health outcomes and reduce the incidence of the complications of diabetes, a formal evaluation has not yet been done.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] In May 2008, the City Council of San Antonio, Texas approved the deployment of an A1C registry for Bexar County.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Authorized by the Texas legislature and the state Health Department, the San Antonio Metropolitan Health District implemented the registry which drew results from all the major clinical laboratories in San Antonio.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] The program was discontinued in 2010 due to lack of funds.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Laboratory surveillance differs from population-wide surveillance because it can only monitor patients who are already receiving medical treatment and therefore having lab tests done.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] For this reason, it does not identify patients who have never been tested.
[src:public-health-informatics/public-health-surveillance] Therefore, it is more suitable for quality management and care improvement than for epidemiological monitoring of an entire population or catchment area.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] A **vaccination policy** is a health policy adopted in order to prevent the spread of infectious disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] These policies are generally put into place by state or local governments, but may also be set by private facilities, such as workplaces or schools.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Many policies have been developed and implemented since vaccines were first made widely available.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The main purpose of implementing a vaccination policy is complete eradication of a disease, as was done with smallpox.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] This, however, can be a difficult feat to accomplish or even confirm.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Many governmental public health agencies (such as the CDC or ECDC) rely on vaccination policies to create a herd immunity within their populations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Immunization advisory committees are usually responsible for providing those in leadership positions with information used to make evidence-based decisions regarding vaccines and other health policies.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Vaccination policies vary from country to country, with some mandating them and others strongly recommending them.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Some places only require them for people utilizing government services, like welfare or public schools.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] A government or facility may pay for all or part of the costs of vaccinations, such as in a national vaccination schedule, or job requirement.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Cost-benefit analyses of vaccinations have shown that there is an economic incentive to implement policies, as vaccinations save the State time and money by reducing the burden preventable diseases and epidemics have on healthcare facilities and funds.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Vaccination policies aim to produce immunity to preventable diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Besides individual protection from getting ill, some vaccination policies also aim to provide the community as a whole with herd immunity.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Herd immunity refers to the idea that the pathogen will have trouble spreading when a significant part of the population has immunity against it, reducing the effect an infectious disease has on society.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] This protects those unable to get the vaccine due to medical conditions, such as immune disorders.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] However, for herd immunity to be effective in a population, a majority of those who are vaccine-eligible must be vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Vaccine-preventable diseases remain a common cause of childhood mortality with an estimated three million deaths each year.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Every year, vaccination prevents between two and three million deaths worldwide, across all age groups, from diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis and measles.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] With some vaccines, a goal of vaccination policies is to eradicate the disease – disappear it from Earth altogether.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) coordinated the effort to eradicate smallpox globally through vaccination, the last naturally occurring case of smallpox was in Somalia in 1977.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Endemic measles, mumps and rubella have been eliminated through vaccination in Finland.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] On 14 October 2010, the UN Food and Agriculture Organization declared that rinderpest had been eradicated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The WHO is currently working to eradicate polio, which was eliminated in Africa in August 2020 and remained only in Pakistan and Afghanistan at the time.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The likely behavior of individuals when offered vaccines can be modeled economically using ideas from game theory.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] According to such models, individuals will attempt to minimize the risk of illness, and may seek vaccination for themselves or their children if they perceive a high threat of disease and a low risk to vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Governments often allow exemptions to mandatory vaccinations for religious or philosophical reasons, but decreased rates of vaccination may cause loss of herd immunity, substantially increasing risks even to vaccinated individuals.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] However, mandatory vaccination policies raise ethical issues regarding parental rights and informed consent.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] At various times, governments and other institutions have established policies requiring vaccination with the aim of reducing the risk of disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] An 1853 law required universal vaccination against smallpox in England and Wales, with fines levied against people who did not comply.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] These policies stirred resistance from a variety of groups, collectively called anti-vaccinationists, who objected on ethical, political, medical safety, religious, and other grounds.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] In the United States, the Supreme Court ruled in *Jacobson v.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Massachusetts* (1905) that states have the authority to require vaccination against smallpox during a smallpox epidemic.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] All fifty U.S. states require that children be vaccinated to attend public school, although 47 states provide exemptions based on religious or philosophical beliefs.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Forced vaccination (as opposed to fines or refusal of services) is uncommon, and typically happens only as an emergency measure during an outbreak.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] This has been reported in parts of China.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Compulsory vaccinations greatly reduce infection rates for the diseases they protect against.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Common objections included the argument that governments should not infringe on individuals' freedom to make medical decisions for themselves or their children, or claims that proposed vaccinations were dangerous.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Many modern vaccination policies allow exemptions for people with compromised immune systems, allergies to vaccination components, or strongly held objections.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] In 1904, in the city of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, following an urban renewal program that displaced many poor, a government program of mandatory smallpox vaccination triggered the Vaccine Revolt, several days of rioting with considerable property damage and a number of deaths.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] An ethical dilemma may emerge when health care providers attempt to persuade vaccine-hesitant families towards receiving vaccinations as this persuasion may lead to violating their autonomy.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] There is also evidence that mandatory vaccination policies for healthcare workers, for instance for influenza shots, increase uptake.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] One argument among public health professionals is that compulsory vaccination is necessary in severe circumstances, but that it should be approached carefully in order to avoid polarizing the population and decreasing trust in the long term.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Many countries (Canada, Germany, Japan, and the United States) have specific requirements for reporting vaccine-related adverse effects; others (Australia, France, and the United Kingdom) include vaccines under their general requirements for reporting injuries associated with medical treatments.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] A number of countries have both compulsory vaccination and national programs for the compensation of injuries alleged to have been caused by a vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] In November 2021, during a COVID-19 outbreak, Austria banned unvaccinated individuals from leaving their home apart from going to work, buying essential supplies, or exercise, in an effort to reduce the spread of disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] During the fourth wave of the COVID-19 pandemic, with a low vaccination rate compared to the rest of Western Europe (79%), the Austrian government made vaccination mandatory.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Medical ethicist Arthur Caplan argues that children have a right to the best available medical care, including vaccines, regardless of parental opinions toward vaccines, saying, "Arguments about medical freedom and choice are at odds with the human and constitutional rights of children.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] When parents won't protect them, governments must." However, government entities, such as Child Protective Services, can intervene only when the parents directly harm their child via abuse or neglect, considering a child does not have the ability to give or take away consent.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Although withholding medical care meets the criteria of abuse or neglect, refusing vaccinations does not, as the child is not being harmed directly.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] To prevent the spread of disease by unvaccinated individuals, some schools and doctors' surgeries have prohibited unvaccinated children from being enrolled, even where not required by law.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Doctors who refuse to treat unvaccinated children harm both the child and public health, and may be considered unethical when parents are unable to find another provider.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Opinion on this is divided, with the largest professional association, the American Academy of Pediatrics, saying that exclusion of unvaccinated children may be an option under narrowly defined circumstances.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] One historical example is the 1990–91 Philadelphia measles outbreak, which led to the deaths of nine children in an anti-vaccination faith healing community.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Court orders were obtained to have infected children given life-saving medical treatment, against the wishes of their parents, and also for healthy children to be vaccinated without parental consent.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Vaccination requirements for access to daycare and schools increase vaccine uptake in the United States and there is evidence that these requirements may decrease disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] However, the majority of studies of mandatory vaccination took place in the US and the cultural climate in United States is quite different from other industrialized nations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] A study shows that many Europeans countries have whooping cough vaccination rates as high as those in the United States despite no mandates.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Canada has a similar vaccination to the US despite 11 of its provinces and territories having no vaccine mandates, which may in part be due to vaccination programs taking place in school in Canada.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Research has increasingly explored behavioral economics strategies to increase voluntary vaccination uptake referred to as '**nudge theory'**.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] These approaches aim to influence decision-making without coercion by altering the context in which choices are made.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Examples include reminder systems, social norm messaging, and educational prompts.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] In Australia, Helen Marshall and colleagues have led research applying nudge theory to improve vaccine uptake among medically at-risk populations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The EPIC study, published in BMJ Open in 2024, tested interventions such as SMS reminders, pledges, and short educational videos to increase COVID-19 and influenza vaccination rates among children with chronic conditions.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Globally, systematic reviews indicate that nudge-based interventions can modestly improve COVID-19 vaccination uptake.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] These behavioral strategies are often discussed alongside debates about compulsory vaccination and exemptions.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Scholars such as Mark Navin argue that while mandates remain common, policies should balance public health goals with respect for parental autonomy.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Navin suggests that nonmedical exemptions should remain available but be made more burdensome to discourage casual refusal, rather than eliminated entirely.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] In the United Kingdom, children are not vaccinated against chickenpox despite the availability of a vaccine since the 1990s.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Modelling predicted that vaccinating children would increase the number of cases amongst adults due to the absence of natural boosting from exposure to chickenpox in day-to-day life.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation were concerned that more pregnant women would become infected because immunity in the general population would decrease .
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Vaccination policy is typically proposed by national or supranational advisory committees on immunization, and in many cases, is regulated by the government.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Predictive vaccination strategy models play an important role in predicting effectiveness of vaccination strategies at population level.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The may, e.g., compare the sequence of age groups to be vaccinated and study the outcome in terms of caseload, deaths, length of a pandemic, healthcare system load, and economic impact.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The promotion of high levels of vaccination produces the protective effect of herd immunity as well as positive externalities in society.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Large scale vaccination is a public good, in that the benefits obtained by an individual from large scale vaccination are both non-rivalrous and non-excludable, and given these traits, individuals may avoid the costs of vaccination by "free-riding" off the benefits of others being vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The costs and benefits to individuals and society have been studied and critiqued in stable and changing population designs.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Other surveys have indicated that free-riding incentives exist in individual decisions, and in a separate study that looked at parental vaccination choice, the study found that parents were less likely to vaccinate their children if their children's friends had already been vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Trust in vaccines and in the health system is an important element of public health programs that aim to deliver life-saving vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Trust in vaccination and health care is an important indicator of government work and the effectiveness of the social policy.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The success in overcoming diseases and in vaccination depends on the level of trust in vaccines and health care.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The lack of trust in vaccines and immunization programs can lead to vaccine refusal, risking disease outbreaks, and challenging immunization goals in high- and low-income settings.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Today, the medical and scientific communities obviously face a big challenge where vaccines are concerned, namely enhancing the trust with which the general public regards the entire endeavor.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Indeed, earning the public's trust in public health is a big challenge.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Accurately, studying the trust in vaccines, and understanding the factors that affect the reduction of trust, allows authorities to build an effective vaccine campaign and communication strategies to fight the disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Trust is a key parameter to work with before and while undertaking any vaccine campaigns.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The state is responsible for providing smart communication, and to inform a population about diseases, vaccines, and the risks of both.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The WHO recommends that states work long-term, to build population resilience against vaccine myths and scares, to develop a strong campaign that is well prepared to respond to any event that may erode trust, and respond immediately to any event which may erode trust in health authorities.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] A review of 34 studies into communication strategies to tackle untruths about vaccines has also suggested strategies that are helpful, such as communicating scientific consensus and using humour to dispel myths, and unhelpful, such as scare tactics.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The first economic analysis of routine childhood immunizations in the United States took place in 2001, and reported cost savings over the lifetime of children born that year.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Other analyses of the economic costs and potential benefits to individuals and society have since been evaluated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] In 2014, the American Academy of Pediatrics published a decision analysis that evaluated direct costs, such as program costs, vaccine cost, administrative burden, negative vaccine-linked reactions, and transportation time lost to parents.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The study focused on several communicable diseases, including diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis, measles, hepatitis A and B, and varicella (chickenpox), but did not include seasonal flu vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Estimated costs and benefits were adjusted to 2009 dollars and projected over time at three percent interest.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Socioeconomic disparities have been found to hinder reasonable access to vaccinations in the U.S., and it has also been found that even if such status is not a factor, "racial ethnic minority adults are less likely than whites to receive preventive care including vaccination".
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] There is an economic incentive to establish vaccination programs for older adults as the general population is aging due to increasing life expectancy and decreasing birth rates.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Vaccinations can reduce the issues linked with both polypharmacy and antibiotic-resistant bacteria in the older demographic with comorbidities by preventing infectious diseases and decreasing the necessity of polypharmacy and antibiotics.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] One 2016 study done in Western Europe found that the estimated cost of vaccinating one person over a lifetime against 10–17 potentially debilitating pathogens would be €443–3,395 (equivalent to €544–4,172 in 2023).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] Another study found that if 75% of adults over 65 were vaccinated against seasonal influenza, 3.2–3.8 million cases and 35,000–52,000 influenza-related deaths could be avoided, and €438–558 million saved annually, solely on the European continent.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] In 2006, the World Health Organization and UNICEF created the Global Immunization Vision and Strategy (GIVS).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p01] The Global Vaccination Action Plan was created by the World Health Organization and endorsed by the World Health Assembly in 2012.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In December 2018, Argentina enacted a new vaccine policy requiring all persons who are medically able, both adults and children, to be vaccinated against specified diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Proof of vaccination is required to attend any level of school, file for a marriage license, and request any kind of government ID, including a passport or driver's license.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The law requires the government to pay for all aspects of vaccinations and deems vaccination to be a national emergency; vaccines are exempt from internal and customs taxes.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In an effort to boost vaccination rates in Australia, the Australian Government decided, starting on 1 January 2016, certain benefits (such as the universal "Family Allowance" welfare payments for parents of children) would no longer be available for conscientious objectors of vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Those with medical grounds for not vaccinating continue to receive such benefits.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The policy is supported by a majority of Australian parents as well as the Australian Medical Association (AMA) and Early Childhood Australia.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In 2014, about 97 percent of children under seven were vaccinated, although the number of conscientious objectors to vaccination had increased by 24,000 to 39,000 in the previous decade.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The government began the Immunise Australia Program to increase national immunization rates.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] They fund a number of different vaccinations for certain groups of people.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The intent is to encourage the most at-risk populations to get vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The government maintains an immunization schedule.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In most states and territories, children can consent to vaccinations if they are judged Gillick competent; normally, this applies to children aged 15 or older.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In South Australia, the *Consent to Medical Treatment and Palliative Care Act 1995* allows children 16 and older to consent to medical treatment.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Additionally, children under this age can be immunized if judged capable of informed consent.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In New South Wales, children can consent to medical treatment at the age of 14.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] When several COVID-19 vaccines were nearing completion in November 2020, Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison announced that all international travelers who fly to Australia without proof of a COVID-19 vaccination would be required to quarantine at their own expense.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] It is also lawful for workplaces in Australia to mandate vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The legality of this was upheld in the Fair Work Commission case *Kimber v Sapphire Coast Community Aged Care Ltd* in 2021.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Austrian vaccine recommendations are developed by the National Vaccination Board (German: *Nationales Impfgremium*), which is part of the Federal Ministry of Social Affairs, Health, Care and Consumer Protection.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Children aged 14 and older can be vaccinated without parental consent.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Vaccinating children has been mandatory in Brazil since 1975, when the federal government instituted the National Immunization Program.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The compulsory character was written into law in 1990, in the Statute of Children and Adolescents (Art.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Parents in Brazil who don't take their children to be vaccinated run the risk of being fined or charged with negligence.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] While vaccination is generally required to attend school in Ontario and New Brunswick, there are exemptions given to those who are opposed.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Under the mature minor doctrine, minors capable of granting informed consent can be vaccinated without parental approval.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] China has passed the World Health Organization's (WHO) regulatory vaccine assessments, demonstrating that they adhere to international standards.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The Chinese government's Expanded Program on Immunization (EPI) was created in 1978 and provides certain obligatory vaccines, named Category 1 vaccines, for free to all children up to 14 years of age.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Initially, the vaccines consisted of Bacillus Calmette-Guérin (BCG) vaccine, oral polio vaccine (OPV), measles vaccine (MV) and diphtheria, tetanus and pertussis (DPT vaccine).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] By 2007, the vaccine list was expanded to include hepatitis A, hepatitis B, Japanese encephalitis, A + C meningococcal polysaccharide, mumps, Rubella, hemorrhagic fever, anthrax, and leptospirosis.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Category 2 vaccines, such as the rabies vaccine, are private-sector, non-obligatory vaccines that are not included in neither EPI nor the government health insurance.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Due to the privatized nature of Category 2 vaccines, these vaccinations are associated with low coverage rates.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Both the Changsheng Bio-Technology Co Ltd and the Wuhan Institute of Biological Products have been fined for selling ineffective vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In December 2018, China enacted new laws imposing strict controls over the production and inspection of aspects of vaccine production from research, development, and testing through production and distribution.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In November 2021, Costa Rica added COVID-19 to the list of infectious diseases required to be vaccinated against.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The vaccine is mandatory for children between the ages of 5 and 18.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In France, the High Council of Public Health is in charge of proposing vaccine recommendations to the Minister of Health.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Each year, immunization recommendations for both the general population and specific groups are published by the Institute of Epidemiology and Surveillance.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Since some hospitals are granted additional freedoms, there are two key people responsible for vaccine policy within hospitals: the Operational physician (OP), and the Head of the hospital infection and prevention committee (HIPC).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Mandatory immunization policies on BCG, diphtheria, tetanus, and poliomyelitis began in the 1950s and policies on Hepatitis B began in 1991.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Recommended but not mandatory suggestions on influenza, pertussis, varicella, and measles began in 2000, 2004, 2004, and 2005, respectively.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] According to the 2013 INPES Peretti-Watel health barometer, between 2005 and 2010, the percentage of French people between 18 and 75 years old in favor of vaccination dropped from 90% to 60%.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Since 2009, France has recommended meningococcus C vaccination for infants 1–2 years old, with a catch up dosage up to 25 years later.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] French insurance companies have reimbursed this vaccine since January 2010, at which point coverage levels were 32.3% for children 1–2 years and 21.3% for teenagers 14–16 years old.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In 2012, the French government and the Institut de veille sanitaire launched a 5-year national program to improve vaccination policy.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The program simplified guidelines, facilitated access to vaccination, and invested in vaccine research.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In 2014, fueled by rare health-related scandals, mistrust of vaccines became a common topic in the French public debate on health.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] According to a French radio station, as of 2014, three to five percent of kids in France were not given the mandatory vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Some families may avoid requirements by finding a doctor willing to forge a vaccination certificate, a solution which numerous French forums confirm.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] However, the French State considers "vaccine refusal" a form of child abuse.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In some instances, parental vaccine refusals may result in criminal trials.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] France's 2010 creation of the Question Prioritaire Constitutionelle (QPC) allows lower courts to refer constitutional questions to the highest court in the relevant hierarchy.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Therefore, criminal trials based on vaccine refusals may be referred to the Cour de Cassation, which will then certify whether the case meets certain criteria.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In May 2015, France updated its vaccination policies on diphtheria, tetanus, acellular pertussis, polio, Haemophilus influenzae b infections, and hepatitis B for premature infants.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] As of 2015, while failure to vaccinate is not necessarily illegal, a parent's right to refuse to vaccinate his or her child is technically a constitutional matter.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Additionally, children in France cannot enter schools without proof of vaccination against diphtheria, tetanus, and polio.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] French Health Minister, Marisol Touraine, finds vaccinations "absolutely fundamental to avoid disease," and has pushed to have trained pharmacists *and* doctors administer vaccinations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Most recently, the Prime Minister's 2015–2017 roadmap for the "multi-annual social inclusion and anti-poverty plan" includes free vaccinations in certain public facilities.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Vaccinations within the immunization schedule are given for free at immunization services within the public sector.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] When given in private medical practices they are reimbursed at 65%.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In Germany, the Standing Committee on Vaccination (STIKO) is the federal commission responsible for recommending an immunization schedule.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The Robert Koch Institute in Berlin (RKI) compiles data of immunization status upon the entry of children at school, and measures vaccine coverage of Germany at a national level.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Founded in 1972, the STIKO is composed of 12–18 volunteers, appointed members by the Federal Ministry for Health for 3-year terms.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Members include experts from many scientific disciplines and public health fields and professionals with extensive experience on vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The independent advisory group meets biannually to address issues pertaining to preventable infectious diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Although the STIKO makes recommendations, immunization in Germany is voluntary and there are no official government recommendations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] German Federal States typically follow the Standing Vaccination Committee's recommendations minimally, although each state can make recommendations for their geographic jurisdiction that extends beyond the recommended list.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In addition to the proposed immunization schedule for children and adults, the STIKO recommends vaccinations for occupational groups, police, travelers, and other at risk groups.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Vaccinations recommendations that are issued must be in accordance with the Protection Against Infection Act (Infektionsschutzgesetz), which regulates the prevention of infectious diseases in humans.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] If a vaccination is recommended because of occupational risks, it must adhere to the Occupational Safety and Health Act involving Biological Agents.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Criteria for the recommendation include disease burden, efficacy and effectiveness, safety, feasibility of program implementation, cost-effectiveness evaluation, clinical trial results, and equity in access to the vaccine.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In the event of vaccination-related injuries, federal states are responsible for monetary compensation.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Germany's central government does not finance childhood immunizations, so 90% of vaccines are administered in a private physician's office and paid for through insurance.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The other 10% of vaccines are provided by the states in public health clinics, schools, or day care centers by local immunization programs.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Physician responsibilities concerning immunization include beginning infancy vaccination, administering booster vaccinations, maintaining medical and vaccination history, and giving information and recommendations concerning vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Children aged 15 and over can legally consent to being vaccinated, even if their parents expressly object, provided the child gives the impression of being mature, informed, and capable of understanding the risks and benefits of their decision.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Beginning in March 2020, Germany made the measles vaccine compulsory for all children attending school or day care, as well persons employed at schools, day cares, and medical or community facilities.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] As of January 2022, COVID-19-vaccination is mandatory for staff and students of secondary and tertiary education, employees in all arms of government, health workers, security personnel, and commercial drivers.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In the Republic of Ireland, childhood vaccination (up to age 16) requires the consent of the parents.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The Department of Health strongly recommend vaccinations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] As aging populations in Italy bring a rising burden of age-related disease, the Italian vaccination system remains complex.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The fact that services and decisions are delivered by 21 separate regional authorities creates many variations in Italian vaccine policy.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] There is a National committee on immunizations that updates the national recommended immunization schedule, with input from the ministry of health representatives, regional health authorities, national institute of health, and other scientific societies.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Regions may add more scheduled vaccinations, but cannot exempt citizens from nationally mandated or recommended ones.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] For instance, a nationwide plan for eliminating measles and rubella began in 2001.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Certain vaccinations in Italy are based on findings from the National Centre for Epidemiology, Surveillance and Health Promotion are also used to determine miscellaneous vaccination mandates.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Childhood vaccinations included in national schedules are guaranteed free of charge for all Italian children and foreign children who live in the country.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Estimated insurance coverage for the required three doses of HBV-Hib-IPV vaccines is at least 95% when the child is two years old.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Influenza is the only nationally necessary vaccine for adults, and is administered by general practitioners.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] To mitigate some public concerns, Italy currently has a national vaccine injury compensation program.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Essentially, those who are ill or damaged by mandatory and recommended vaccinations may receive funding from the government as compensation.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] A 2010 evaluation of vaccine coverage, which covered the 2008 birth cohort, showed a slight decline in immunization insurance coverage rates of diphtheria, hepatitis B, polio, and tetanus after those specific vaccinations had been made mandatory.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] However, vaccination levels continued to pass the Italian government's goal of 95% outreach.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Aiming to integrate immunization strategies across the country and equitize access to disease prevention, the Italian Ministry of Health issued the National Immunization Prevention Plan (Piano Nazionale Prevenzione Vaccinale) in 2012.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] This plan for 2012–2014 introduced an institutional "life course" approach to vaccination to complement the Italian health policy agenda.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] HPV vaccine coverage increased well, and pneumococcal vaccine and meningococcal C vaccines faced positive public reception.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] However, both infant vaccine coverage rates and influenza immunization in the elderly have been decreasing.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] A 2015 government plan in Italy aimed to boost vaccination rates and introduce a series of new vaccines, triggering protests among public health professionals.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Partially in response to the statistic that less than 86% of Italian children receive the measles shot, the National Vaccination Plan for 2016–18 (PNPV) increased vaccination requirements.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] For instance, nationwide varicella shots would be required for newborns.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Under this plan, government spending on vaccines would double to €620 million annually, and children could be barred from attending school without proving vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Although these implementations would make Italy a European frontrunner in vaccination, some experts questioned the need for several of the vaccines, and some physicians worried about the potential punishment they may face if they do not comply with the proposed regulations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] This rise accounted for 29% of all those in the European Union.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The law compelling children to have ten vaccinations to enroll at state schools came into effect in March 2018 but in August 2018 the Five Star Movement pushed legislation through the Italian Senate abolishing it.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] It did not pass the Chamber of Deputies but parents did not have to provide schools with a doctor's note to show their children have been vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] By November 2018, the government had changed its stance because of the "measles emergency" and decided to uphold the obligation for children up to the age of 16, teachers and health professionals to be vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] A midwife working at a hospital in central Italy was terminated for refusing vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In Japan, there are three types of vaccination practices: Routine (scheduled); Temporary (ad-hoc); and Non-legal.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Infections of the first two types are defined by Immunization Act (Japanese: 予防接種法) and its related cabinet order (Japanese: 予防接種法施行令).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] As of January 2020, sixteen infections in total are on the legal lists – fourteen are Category A diseases (vaccination is not mandatory but recommended to prevent pandemic), and two are Category B (not even recommended and only for a personal care purpose).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Compared to the global standard, Japanese vaccination policy is sometimes described by medical experts as the "Vaccine Gap." For instance, Japan is the only developed country that does not list mumps on the vaccine schedule.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] It's also noted that the government approval for new combination vaccines usually takes longer than other developed countries, such as the United States.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] One reason behind the vaccine gap is that the government was sued several times for negligence of duty of care and for malpractice liabilities throughout the vaccination history.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The lawsuit risks, particularly the 1992 Tokyo High Court's ruling on the MMR vaccine class action, impacted on law amendment.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] Vaccination is no longer mandatory as of 1994.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] As a result, vaccination rate declined in Japan.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The rate of flu vaccination, for example, was 67.9% among schoolchildren in 1979 but dropped down to approximately 20% in 1998–1999.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] With the rapidly aging society issue, the decline among schoolchildren hit the elderly generation.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] In 1998–1999 season, deadly flu outbreak spread widely in nursing homes for the elderly as well as inpatients wards.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] The outbreak was followed by the 2001 amendment of Immunization Act to add flu vaccination for the elderly.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] As of February 2020, flu vaccination under the Act is in Category B (for a personal care purpose) only for the elderly.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p02] However, historical data sets suggest that flu vaccination for schoolchildren is also the key to take care of the elderly.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In addition to legal and social risk concerns, an issue of the decision-making process underlies the vaccine gap.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Unlike the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP) in the United States, a centralized permanent advisory committee for vaccination policy was not organized in Japan until 2009, when a deadly flu outbreak struck the nation.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Since the committee kick-off, however, the vaccine gap has been gradually improved.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] HPV vaccine in Japan refers to the national history of human papillomavirus immunization policy, beginning with the vaccine's initial approval in 2009.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] It was incorporated into the routine immunization schedule in 2013.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] However, in June of that year, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (MHLW) suspended proactive recommendation due to reports of adverse events.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Vaccination rates subsequently dropped below 1%.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] After years of scientific review, international pressure, and domestic advocacy, proactive recommendation was resumed in 2022.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] According to a 2011 publication in *CMAJ*: The notion of "mandatory" in Latvia differs from that of other nations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Latvia appears unique in that it compels health care providers to obtain the signatures of those who decline vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Individuals have the right to refuse a vaccination, but if they do so, health providers have a duty to explain the health consequences.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Vaccines that are not mandatory are not publicly funded, so the cost for those must be borne by parents or employers, she adds.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Funded vaccinations include tuberculosis, diphtheria, measles, hepatitis B, human papillomavirus for 12-year-old girls, and tick-borne encephalitis until age 18 in endemic areas and for orphans.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Beginning at age 14, minors can consent to vaccination in Latvia without parental permission.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] COVID-19 vaccination is mandatory for health workers, journalists, and other frontline staff starting 20 December 2021.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In Malaysia, mass vaccination is practised in public schools.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The vaccines may be administered by a school nurse or a team of other medical staff from outside the school.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] All the children in a given school year are vaccinated as a cohort.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] For example, children may receive the oral polio vaccine in Year One of primary school (about six or seven years of age), the BCG in Year Six, and the MMR in Form Three of secondary school.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Therefore, most people have received their core vaccines by the time they finish secondary school.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Mexico has a multi-year program for immunisation of children.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The immunisation of children is fully covered by the government.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Mexico has an adverse events committee to monitor the adverse effects of vaccination as well as a standing technical advisory group on immunization.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The recommended vaccine schedule for children in Mexico contains vaccinations against 16 vaccine-preventable diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Vaccine doses administered in Mexico are usually valid in the United States.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In addition, Vitamin A is offered to all children of one year of age enrolled in nurseries or children's rooms.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Minors aged 16 and older may consent to vaccination without parental approval.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In Nigeria, the Expanded Programme on Immunization (EPI), was introduced in 1978 to provide free immunization against polio, measles, diphtheria, whooping cough, tuberculosis, and yellow fever to Nigerian children less than two years old.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] This free immunization can be obtained at any primary healthcare provider in the country.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The vaccines are usually administered by a government health care worker.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] They also conduct routine vaccination visits in schools where all the children in a given school are vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Facing numerous minor polio epidemics, the Pakistani government has now ruled that polio vaccination is mandatory and indisputable.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In a statement from Pakistani Police Commissioner Riaz Khan Mehsud, "There is no mercy, we have decided to deal with the refusal cases with iron hands.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] COVID-19 vaccination may become mandatory for government employees.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Unvaccinated employees may be forced to take unpaid leave.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Having completed the vaccine schedule for schoolchildren up to the child's age, is required for access to the government's main scholarship program.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] As of 2019, immunization is voluntary in Russia.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In the wake of a declared measles epidemic, Samoan authorities made vaccination against measles compulsory in November 2019.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] According to a 2011 publication in *CMAJ*: Slovenia has one of the world's most aggressive and comprehensive vaccination programs.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Its program is mandatory for nine designated diseases.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Within the first three months of life, infants must be vaccinated for tuberculosis, tetanus, polio, pertussis, and Haemophilus influenza type B.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Within 18 months, vaccines are required for measles, mumps, and rubella, and finally, before a child starts school, the child must be vaccinated for hepatitis B.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] While a medical exemption request can be submitted to a committee, such an application for reasons of religion or conscience would not be acceptable.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Failure to comply results in a fine and compliance rates top 95%, Kraigher says, adding that for nonmandatory vaccines, such as the one for human papillomavirus, coverage is below 50%.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Mandatory vaccination against measles was introduced in 1968 and since 1978, all children receive two doses of vaccine with a compliance rate of more than 95%.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] For TBE, the vaccination rate in 2007 was estimated to be 12.4% of the general population in 2007.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] For comparison, in neighboring Austria, 87% of the population is vaccinated against TBE.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In South Africa vaccination is voluntary.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The South African Vaccination and Immunisation Centre (SAVIC) began in 2003 as an alliance between the South African Department of Health, vaccine industry, academic institutions, and other stakeholders.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] SAVIC works with the WHO and the South African National Department of Health to educate, research, provide technical support, and advocate for country-wide vaccinations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Spain's 19 autonomous communities, consisting of 17 Regions and two cities, follow health policies established by the Inter-Territorial Health Council that was formed by the National and Regional Ministries of Health.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] This Inter-Territorial Council is composed of representatives from each region and meets to discuss health related issues spanning across Spain.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The Institute of Health Carlos III (ISCIIII) is a public research institute that manages biomedical research for the advancement of health sciences and disease preventions.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The ISCIII may suggest the introduction of new vaccines into Spain's Recommended Health Schedule and is under direct control of the Ministry of Health.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Although the Ministry of Health is responsible for the oversight of health care services, the policy of devolution divides responsibilities among local agencies, including health planning and programing, fiscal duties, and direct management of health services.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] This decentralization proposes difficulties in collecting information at the national level.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The Inter-Territorial Council's Commission on Public Health works to establish health care policies according to recommendations by technical working groups via letters, meetings, and conferences.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The Technical Working Group on Vaccines review data on vaccine preventable diseases and proposes recommendations for policies.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] No additional groups outside the government propose recommendations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Recommendations must be approved by the Commission of Public Health and then by the Inter-Territorial Council, at which point they are incorporated into the National Immunization Schedule.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The Spanish Association of Pediatrics, in conjunction with the Spanish Medicines Agency, outlines specifications for vaccination schedules and policies and provides a history of vaccination policies implemented in the past, as well as legislature pertaining to the public currently.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Spain's Constitution does not mandate vaccination, so it is voluntary unless authorities require compulsory vaccination in the case of epidemics.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In 1921, vaccination became mandatory for smallpox, and in 1944 the Bases Health Act mandated compulsory vaccination for diphtheria and smallpox, but was suspended in 1979 after the elimination of the threat of an epidemic.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The first systematic immunization schedule for the provinces of Spain was established in 1975 and has continuously been updated by each autonomous community in regard to doses at certain ages and recommendation of additional vaccine not proposed in the schedule.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The 2015 schedule proposed the newest change with the inclusion of pneumococcal vaccine for children under 12 months.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] For 2016, the schedule plans to propose a vaccine against varicella in children at 12–15 months and 3–4 years.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Furthermore, the General Health Law of 1986 echoes Article 40.2 from the Constitution guaranteeing the right to the protection of health, and states employers must provide vaccines to workers if they are at risk of exposure.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Due to vaccination coverage in each Community, there is little anti-vaccine activity or opposition to the current schedule, and no organized groups against vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The universal public health care provides coverage for all residents, while central and regional support programs extend coverage to immigrant populations.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] However, no national funds are granted to the Communities for vaccine purchases.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Vaccines are financed from taxes, and paid in full by the Community government.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Law 21 in Article 2.6 establishes the need for proper clinical documentation and informed consent by the patient, although written informed consent is not mandated in the verbal request of a vaccine for a minor.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The autonomous regions collect data, from either electronic registries or written physician charts, to calculate immunization coverage.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The Swiss vaccination schedule and recommendations are developed by the Federal Vaccination Commission and the Federal Office of Public Health in collaboration with the cantons.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Minors aged 12 and older may consent to immunization with the Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine without parental approval.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] According to the World Health Organization vaccination coverage in Tanzania was more than 90% in 2012.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] An Electronic Immunisation Register has been established, which permits online access to the medical records of mothers and infants, enabling vaccination teams in remote areas to operate more effectively, especially with nomadic people.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] It also helps to coordinate stock levels and order new supplies.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In the United Kingdom, the purchase and distribution of vaccines is managed centrally, and recommended vaccines are provided for free by the NHS.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In the UK, no laws require vaccination of schoolchildren.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Children aged 16 and 17 can consent to immunizations without parental consent.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Under the Gillick test, children under 16 can consent to vaccination over parental objections if they demonstrate a mature understanding of the ramifications of the procedure.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In the United States, the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices makes scientific recommendations regarding vaccines and vaccination schedules that the federal government, state governments, and private health insurance companies generally follow.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] See Vaccination schedule for the schedule recommended in the United States.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] As of 2025, all states in the U.S. except for Idaho mandate immunizations for children to enroll in public school, but various exemptions are available depending on the state.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] An increasing number of parents are using religious and philosophical exemptions: researchers have cited this increased use of exemptions as contributing to loss of herd immunity within these communities, and hence an increasing number of disease outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Of the 49 states with existing immunization requirements for public school, all of them require DTaP (diphtheria-tetanus-pertussis), MMR (measles-mumps-rubella), Polio, Tdap (tetanus-diphtheria-pertussis; secondary school only) and Varicella (chickenpox) vaccines for school attendance.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Additionally, 46 states require the Hepatitis B vaccine, 34 states require the Meningococcal vaccine, and 18 require the Hepatitis A vaccine; Rhode Island, Virginia, and Hawaii also require the HPV vaccine (human papillomavirus; secondary school only).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) advises physicians to respect the refusal of parents to vaccinate their child after adequate discussion, unless the child is put at significant risk of harm (e.g., during an epidemic, or after a deep and contaminated puncture wound).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Under such circumstances, the AAP states that parental refusal of immunization constitutes a form of medical neglect and should be reported to state child protective services agencies.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Several states allow minors to legally consent to vaccination over parental objections under the mature minor doctrine.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Immunizations are compulsory for military enlistment in the U.S.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] However, exceptions exist, but may be determined by an uneven process.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The judge had previously awarded class action status to the case, extending the suit to cover an estimated more than 12,000 joint plaintiffs.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] All vaccines recommended by the U.S. government for its citizens are required for green card applicants.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] This requirement stirred controversy over related costs when, in July 2008, it was applied to the HPV vaccine.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In addition, the 13 other required vaccines prevent highly contagious diseases communicable through the respiratory route, while HPV is spread only through sexual contact.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In November 2009, this requirement was canceled.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Though the federal guidelines do not require written consent to receive a vaccination, they do require doctors give the recipients or legal representatives a Vaccine Information Statement (VIS).
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Specific informed consent laws are made by the states.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The United States has a long history of school vaccination requirements.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The first school vaccination requirement was enacted in the 1850s in Massachusetts to prevent the spread of smallpox.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The school vaccination requirement was put in place after the compulsory school attendance law caused a rapid increase in the number of children in public schools, increasing the risk of smallpox outbreaks.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The early movement towards school vaccination laws began at the local level including counties, cities, and boards of education.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] By 1827, Boston had become the first city to mandate that all children entering public schools show proof of vaccination.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] By 1963, 20 states had school vaccination laws.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] These vaccination laws resulted in political debates throughout the United States, as those opposed to vaccination sought to repeal local policies and state laws.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] An example of this political controversy occurred in 1893, in Chicago, where less than ten percent of the children were vaccinated, despite the twelve-year-old state law.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Resistance was seen at the local level of the school district as some local school boards and superintendents opposed the state vaccination laws, leading the state board health inspectors to examine vaccination policies in schools.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Resistance proceeded during the mid-1900s and in 1977 a nationwide Childhood Immunization Initiative was developed with the goal of increasing vaccination rates among children to ninety percent by 1979.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] During the two-year period of observation, the initiative reviewed the immunization records of more than 28 million children and vaccinated children who had not received the recommended vaccines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In 1922, the constitutionality of childhood vaccination was examined in the Supreme Court case *Zucht v.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The court decided that a school could deny admission to children who failed to provide a certification of vaccination for the protection of the public health.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In 1987, there was a measles epidemic in Maricopa County, Arizona, and *Maricopa County Health Department v.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Harmon* examined the arguments of an individual's right to education over the state's need to protect against the spread of disease.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The court decided that it is prudent to take action to combat the spread of disease by denying unvaccinated children a place in school until the risk for the spread of measles had passed.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Schools in the United States require an updated immunization record for all incoming and returning students.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] While all states require an immunization record, this does not mean all students must get vaccinated.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Exemptions are determined at a state level.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In the United States, exemptions take one of three forms: medical, in which a vaccine is contraindicated because of a component ingredient allergy or existing medical condition; religious; and personal philosophical opposition.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Until 2015, only Mississippi and West Virginia did not permit religious exemptions.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] However, this changed after California removed personal and religious exemptions with the passage of California Senate Bill 277.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] This is the first time an immunization exemption was removed by a state legislature.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] The bill was prompted by the 2014 Disneyland measles outbreak and low levels of vaccination in pockets of California, with some schools having vaccination rates below 60%.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Throughout the 2020s, some states have loosened their immunization policies for schools.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In July 2023, Mississippi started recognizing religious exemptions at the order of a judge, and in January 2025, West Virginia governor Patrick Morrisey issued an executive order allowing religious exemptions in the state, though the order has not been enforced by the state's Board of Education.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In April 2025, Idaho became the first and only state to remove immunization requirements for schools after the passage of Senate Bill 1210.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Research studies have found a correlation between the rise of vaccine-preventable diseases and non-medical exemptions from school vaccination requirements, however, mandatory vaccination requirements for attending public schools have received criticism.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Parents say that vaccine mandates to attend public schools prevent one's right to choose, especially if the vaccinations could be harmful.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Some people believe being forced to get a vaccination could cause trauma, and may lead to not seeking medical care/attention ever again.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] In the constitutional law, some states have the liberty to withdraw to public health regulations, which includes mandatory vaccination laws that threaten fines.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] Certain laws are being looked at for immunization requirements, and are trying to be changed, but cannot succeed due to legal challenges.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] After California removed non-medical exemptions for school entrance, lawsuits were filed arguing for the right for children to attend school regardless of their vaccination history, and to suspend the bill's implementation altogether.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] However, all such lawsuits ultimately failed.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] As of 2022, 300 American colleges and universities mandate that their students receive a COVID-19 booster.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] A study in the Journal of Medical Ethics concludes that the cost of these mandates likely outweigh the benefits.
[src:public-health-informatics/vaccination-policy-p03] For example, to prevent one COVID hospitalization over a 6-month period, 31,000 to 42,000 adults in that age group would have to get a third mRNA booster; and those boosters will result in at least 18 "serious adverse events" (SAEs) for that single prevented hospitalization.
